WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.840
 >> Hi, Ray. How are you doing?

00:00:03.840 --> 00:00:06.000
 >> I'm doing very well.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.160
 >> Great. Well, I'm just -- I feel just thrilled to be speaking with you today.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:17.200
 I love that you expressed interest in this topic of education.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:19.160
 And I'm really excited about this.

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:21.480
 I think it'll be a great one.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:23.040
 The topic is education.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:32.880
 In other words, how can we grow a rich, dynamic, and just a quality education in the year 2020 and beyond.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:34.000
 What does this look like?

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.040
 How can it be cultivated?

00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:40.600
 I think you're a great person to talk to when it comes to this.

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:46.520
 Would you mind, I think, for our listeners, the people who might listen to this and enjoy this,

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:49.240
 would you mind going into your background?

00:00:49.240 --> 00:00:55.720
 Why are you such a good person to listen to when it comes to education?

00:00:55.720 --> 00:01:04.600
 >> Oh, I actually started thinking about education when I was about eight years old.

00:01:04.600 --> 00:01:15.160
 We moved to Oregon from San Diego, and I had a couple of years at a very tiny school.

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:20.240
 I think there were a dozen students in eighth grades.

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:28.440
 And so as a third grader, I got to listen to the lessons for all of the grades.

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:47.400
 And when I got to the junior high, I realized I had already heard the lessons for a couple of years previously.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:02:03.960
 And we had a little encyclopedia published about 1930, and it had an article about experimental schools.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:13.400
 And I heard about Bertrand Russell's, the private school he started, and his wife.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:24.400
 And that really got me thinking how good the experience was in that tiny country school.

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:33.960
 And then when I got to the city schools, how regimented and deadening it was.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:44.960
 So all the way through high school, I experienced that stifling effect of most of the classes.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:57.880
 For example, the biology teacher at 10th grade biology refused to talk about evolution.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:05.880
 Wow. Most of the teachers were similarly backward.

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:17.800
 There were two or three very good people, and I realized that getting to know enlightened people was the thing, not taking their courses.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:27.800
 When I went to college, a little state college, I sampled all of the required courses.

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:37.800
 And similarly, most of them were taught by people who basically just surveyed what was in the textbook.

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:45.800
 Some of them literally wrote everything out on the blackboard laboriously.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:04:07.800
 And I had a couple of good introductory science courses that the people actually took teaching seriously and wanted to get the main ideas across.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:27.800
 But accidentally, I heard about a literature professor who had a reputation for being a hard grader, but the literature instructor I had first was just impossibly tedious.

00:04:27.800 --> 00:04:45.800
 So I switched over to the one with the reputation of being a hard grader and found that he was actually just talking to his students and explaining how he saw each of the periods of literature,

00:04:45.800 --> 00:05:04.800
 and revealing that he had a big picture of what's going on in the world and that each phase of literature was a way of seeing the world from different perspectives.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:23.800
 So I had the expectation that graduate school might have other people like that and found that they were even scarcer in graduate school than in a little state college.

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:46.800
 So first I got a General Studies Master's degree in which I was able to pick out professors that I thought were sane and then do a one-to-one reading and conference sort of tutorial with them

00:05:46.800 --> 00:06:01.800
 and went on to specialize in linguistics and found a couple of professors for similar one-to-one tutorials.

00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:26.800
 But that was in 1959 and '60. The master's was '56, '57. And at that time, the best of the professors had to be extremely cautious.

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:55.800
 For example, the atmospheric bomb tests were going on, and it was, if anyone criticized militarism or the dangers of dumping radioactive fallout onto populations, they were fired from their government jobs and cut off from all sorts of communication.

00:06:55.800 --> 00:07:19.800
 If a professor signed a petition opposing war or bomb testing and they lost their tenure and/or got fired, the atmosphere was probably just about as bad as the 1930s under Hitler.

00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:30.800
 But no one really talked about it in the U.S. because it was defined as how democracy works.

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:47.800
 So it sounds like it's not just that these teachers, so many of your teachers, so many of the teachers that we probably have all had, were just doing their job and doing what they had learned to do, collecting a paycheck, but it was also that they were afraid in some ways.

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:51.800
 It took a lot of guts to teach differently, perhaps.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:08:09.800
 Yeah, in one of my literature seminars, the issue of, you know, lots of the famous 18th century literary figures were members of the ruling class.

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:30.800
 And I mentioned something about the present effect of class on literature and viewpoints, and the professor interrupted me and said, "There are no classes in the United States."

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.800
 Unbelievable. Wow.

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:42.800
 So no one was encouraged then to think for themselves. How did anyone make it out thinking differently?

00:08:42.800 --> 00:09:00.800
 I got a job teaching at college that year and was assigned to teach introduction to physics for biology majors as one of my courses.

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:20.800
 And the president of the college said what he wanted was for the students to be able to understand what they read in the newspapers as well as have the information they should know as a biology freshman.

00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:46.800
 And since the issues in the newspapers related to a lot of discussion of atom bombs and nuclear energy and quite a bit of discussion about computers, I decided that those would be good themes to talk about.

00:09:46.800 --> 00:10:03.800
 And so I discussed how energy, what energy means to an organism and what ionizing radiation does to a cell.

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:15.800
 And it happened that in the spring term, a visitor from University of Illinois came to give a lecture.

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:34.800
 He was invited without assigning a topic. And when he got there, he lectured on the biological effects of radioactive isotopes, just what I had been talking to my students about.

00:10:34.800 --> 00:11:00.800
 And that week he was fired from his job at the University of Illinois without mentioning his anti-war, anti-bomb test position, but accusing him of supporting sexual freedom among college students.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:14.800
 But the effect of his lecture on radiation was disturbing to the administrators at my college.

00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:34.800
 And it ended up with me getting fired. And that immediately led me to think about the general issue of college education.

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:47.800
 Modelling it, for example, on Bertrand Russel's and the other experimental schools I had read about in the early part of the century.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:52.800
 So I decided to start my own college.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:12:07.800
 And the professor from Illinois was going on a lecture tour about academic freedom, and he was in the news pursuing the University of Illinois.

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:19.800
 And in his lectures he mentioned that we were starting a college that would be free from intervention by trustees.

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:41.800
 And so we gathered up some students, and I found that the boards of education in the United States wouldn't let you give a transcript if you didn't have a certain amount of money behind you.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:55.800
 But if you had an endowment of some sort, buildings or property, then you could, in effect, sell your degrees and transcripts.

00:12:55.800 --> 00:13:11.800
 It was legal to have a degree bill, but not to give even a letter saying that the student had been there if you didn't have money that you had at risk.

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:18.800
 So if you said the wrong thing, the state could shut you down and take your money.

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:24.800
 My gosh, so just like all these other institutions, it's just been a business.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:35.800
 Yeah, I went to -- that was in California, and I went to Oregon thinking they might have a different attitude.

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:56.800
 The assistant secretary of education or public instruction ended our conversation saying "it doesn't matter, education isn't about what students know."

00:13:56.800 --> 00:14:11.800
 I mean, I'm not surprised because I've been reading a lot of various viewpoints and listening to some of the things you said, but it really troubles me.

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:15.800
 I mean, it's deeply disconcerting.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:27.800
 Just back to Blake College, and you said Bertrand Russell was an early influence of yours, and you talked about the experimental school where he and his wife had built.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:37.800
 What were some of the educational practices or some of the educational philosophies that they had going that worked their way into what you did with Blake College?

00:14:37.800 --> 00:14:59.800
 Just to recognize that each student was an individual, pretty much the same thing that A.S. Neal did at Summerhill, just to recognize that everyone is in the world wanting to understand it.

00:14:59.800 --> 00:15:09.800
 And they dealt with that, whatever the individual wanted to know and needed to know.

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:23.800
 What did you do at Blake with students that allowed them to get to know themselves better and to get to form opinions without, you know, outside influence?

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:42.800
 For example, at one point we had an old hotel and several instructors and students had rooms in the same building.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:52.800
 So a professor could say, "At home, I teach courses," and so on and so forth.

00:15:52.800 --> 00:16:02.800
 And students, if they thought that was interesting, one of them would say, "Well, we'd like to hear you talk about that."

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:25.800
 All of the other students who were interested would get together and spend maybe five or six hours continuously in conversation, and typically they would cover at least a semester's coursework at home in one sitting.

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:34.800
 It really just sounds so good to me that someone gets to decide what they want to do, that everything's optional.

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:44.800
 And then if they wanted to, for example, pass national exams that show they were ready for grad school or whatever, that this was something they could do also, right?

00:16:44.800 --> 00:16:56.800
 Yeah, they took the Graduate Record exam General Studies -- I forget the -- oh, they were called Area Tests.

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:12.800
 They had the departmental tests, history, math, biology, and so on, but they had the Area Tests that were given at that time to graduating seniors across the U.S.

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:28.800
 And so if you scored 50th percentile on the three Area Tests, that was typical of a graduate of a four-year college in the U.S.

00:17:28.800 --> 00:17:42.800
 It was humanities, general, social studies, and science were the three areas.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:54.800
 And we just set arbitrarily the idea that we wanted the students to have the experience of what it was to be there.

00:17:54.800 --> 00:18:06.800
 And so we said you had to be here six months, two quarters, participating, and then you could take the test.

00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:22.800
 And they averaged -- after only six months, the students who took the tests, I think their average was 92nd percentile.

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:30.800
 Wow, Ray, I love how you're talking about the relationship aspect and the one-to-one opportunity,

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:36.800
 and just that you mentioned earlier that, like, if you wanted to -- if you want to learn, then it's the relationship.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:37.800
 It's not the classes.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:39.800
 It's not the things that you're studying.

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:40.800
 It's the relationships.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:44.800
 It's interpersonal communication and being with people.

00:18:44.800 --> 00:18:51.800
 Do you think that the people who attended Blake College were generally feeling the same way?

00:18:51.800 --> 00:18:52.800
 Did they love it?

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.800
 Were they happy?

00:18:54.800 --> 00:19:02.800
 One guy said that he was considered sort of retarded.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:11.800
 He had scored something like the fourth percentile on some tests that he had taken in high school.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:37.800
 And he was only there for 10 weeks, but we let him take the test just because he was a special problem that believed he was not up to the standard.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:50.800
 But after just 10 weeks, he scored the 50th percentile ranking with equal of the average United States college graduate.

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:57.800
 So was it that he was accepted and allowed to find his personhood and explore?

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:04.800
 I mean cos that's got to be a part of this, right, like the confidence that goes with being able to do what you want grows?

00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:19.800
 One of our people, he had been a TV quiz kid on one of the TV shows.

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:30.800
 He was a straight A student, so they had a panel of supposedly very bright, well-educated kids.

00:20:30.800 --> 00:20:48.800
 He said he didn't know how to think, and what he wanted to do was just put himself together so that he could think with his knowledge because he said it was completely useless to him.

00:20:48.800 --> 00:21:02.800
 That's awesome that you were giving opportunities to people like that who maybe were labeled as smart, right, like labeled as people who they received the information out of a book well and they can spit it out.

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:11.800
 They could regurgitate information, but that had nothing to do with thinking, and it's cool that even the individual recognized the importance of that.

00:21:11.800 --> 00:21:14.800
 One of the things you said reminded me of A.S. Neal.

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:20.800
 He said once that a good teacher does not draw out, he gives out, and what he gives out is love.

00:21:20.800 --> 00:21:24.800
 And by love, I mean approval, or if you like, friendliness, good nature.

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:29.800
 The good teacher not only understands the child, he approves of the child.

00:21:29.800 --> 00:21:32.800
 Do you care to add anything to that?

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:37.800
 Yeah, do you know Carl Rogers and his client-centered therapy?

00:21:37.800 --> 00:21:40.800
 I've read a little bit of his stuff now, yeah.

00:21:40.800 --> 00:21:57.800
 That was one of my -- while I was a psychology major in graduate school for a while, I had a professor that introduced me to people like Carl Rogers.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:12.800
 And his thing was unconditional positive regard was therapeutic in the treatment situation, but it's also educational.

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:21.800
 It's essential for learning and teaching just as much as for psychotherapy.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:28.800
 I love that. It reminded me of -- and I don't know how familiar you are with Nietzsche or what you think of Nietzsche,

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:40.800
 but apparently, from my understanding, there's this thing called Amor Fasci, or amor Fati, and one of his translations I saw that he said,

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:50.800
 "My formula for greatness in a human being is Amor Fati, that one wants nothing to be different, not forward, not backward, not in all eternity,

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:58.800
 not merely bearing what is necessary, and still less concealing it, but rather loving it."

00:22:58.800 --> 00:22:59.800
 And I don't know.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:10.800
 To me, that speaks a little bit to, like, that in order to change something or to see challenges and come up with new solutions, you kind of got to start where you are.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:11.800
 And I don't know.

00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:13.800
 Do you have anything to add to that?

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:21.800
 Yeah, you know John Dewey's famous phrase that "education isn't preparation for life,

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:23.800
 it is life itself."

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:27.800
 Oh, I like that. I like that.

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:42.800
 Another philosopher, psychologist that I think was very insightful and useful was Eric (Ernest) Schachtel, who wrote the book Metamorphosis.

00:23:42.800 --> 00:24:09.800
 And, in that he has the ideas of Allocentric Perception starting in infancy, in which you learn to see empathy, basically, to see that there are other beings and to learn to let your involvement go out

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:14.800
 and have them participate in a personal way.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:43.800
 But the way things are set up, people start what he called Secondary Autocentric Perception, in which things are understood and valued only as they are useful in your little

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:52.800
 Self-contained world. You don't go out of yourself. You bring everything useful into your control.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:56.800
 Why do you think it is that we learn to do that?

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:16.800
 The attitude towards language of the parents and the schools, it usually gets built in by the time a kid starts school with the parents telling them what to believe, basically,

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:36.800
 not introducing them to the richness and possibilities of each thing as a complexity that remains to be understood, but giving finished answers

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:50.800
 and giving them a world ready to use, but not to get too involved in personally.

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:57.800
 Oh, I like that. A.S. Neil, in his writing on Summerhill, he did write something about that.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:06.800
 He also wrote something about that where he talked about how rare it was for him to -- in fact, he didn't even know if his own children were able to be self-regulated

00:26:06.800 --> 00:26:13.800
 and develop kind of their own way of looking at things. It was just such a challenge for him.

00:26:13.800 --> 00:26:39.800
 The teacher really can't do anything more than be enthusiastic about living and discovering, and that can't avoid being communicated if the teacher is really living his life that way.

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:50.800
 I like that. What else do you think a teacher should be in the most valuable sense? What can a teacher's role be?

00:26:50.800 --> 00:27:17.800
 Oh, everyone has accumulated lots of experiences, and so being -- sharing your perspective on your experiences expands when someone is really listening to you.

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:41.800
 Everything you say is flavored by your experiences, and so when you expand on describing your experiences and perspectives, you're intelligible to the person who is seeing them as part of your personality.

00:27:41.800 --> 00:28:03.800
 You aren't saying, "Here is this definitely known bit of stuff that you could stuff into your memory, but here is the pattern of problems that I experienced."

00:28:03.800 --> 00:28:32.800
 And just in using language, you're always ultimately asking your listener to invent what I'm saying. You have to share your minds and I'll invent it while I'm saying it if you will invent it along with me.

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:40.800
 Yeah, I like that. And then when I go share my version of what we talked about, it's going to be another creation, right?

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:56.800
 Yeah, Alfred North Whitehead made that very explicit when he said, "No sentence is complete and explicit in itself. It always implies everything."

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:05.800
 I think that's great. Is that part of what -- I think he had his fundamental stages of learning, romance, precision, and generalization? Is that part of the generalization phase?

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:31.800
 Yeah, yeah. What is most personal is also most general and universal. If you really are involved in something and share that involvement, it involves the whole world as you understand it.

00:29:31.800 --> 00:29:36.800
 So personal and universal can't be separated.

00:29:36.800 --> 00:29:52.800
 Wow. Didn't Ralph Waldo Emerson in his essay on self-reliance speak to that, saying something like, "Whatever is felt by me is true for everyone." I think he expressed it differently, but is that kind of what he was getting at?

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:57.800
 Yeah, Emerson was very good.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:30:08.800
 I heard one of my buddies philosophy, PhD, and he learned -- he became fluent in German so he could study Hegel and Nietzsche.

00:30:08.800 --> 00:30:17.800
 And one of the stories he told me about Nietzsche was that he carried around a book bag with him a lot, wherever he went, and it had books, his favorite books.

00:30:17.800 --> 00:30:28.800
 And he -- I guess my buddy was telling me that he abhorred American writers with the exception of Emerson. He carried around essays of Emerson.

00:30:28.800 --> 00:30:35.800
 He loved reading Emerson. It always made him happy and helped his thinking, I guess.

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:43.800
 Emerson was really much more radical than people think.

00:30:43.800 --> 00:30:55.800
 One of the things you said earlier, Ray, I thought was interesting about the -- everyone's literature or literature from different periods gives us a window into that time period.

00:30:55.800 --> 00:31:06.800
 And then you said later about when we share stories, when we talk about what we're excited about, that that might be a window for someone else into some new world.

00:31:06.800 --> 00:31:21.800
 And it got me thinking about Tolstoy for some reason, because I remember reading somewhere that Tolstoy started an experimental school, and apparently he taught -- he didn't teach writing in any kind of traditional way.

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:33.800
 He just wanted people to write, and he wanted people's stories to come out, and he wanted the content to come out, and he didn't grade or look at punctuation or grammar, because he thought that eventually that would just correct itself.

00:31:33.800 --> 00:31:39.800
 What he really wanted was the story, what someone was trying to say, and just write that.

00:31:39.800 --> 00:31:59.800
 Yeah, I didn't know that about Tolstoy, but I, at Montana State, was given two or three writing courses every term, and the department had instructions on how to grade papers and how to flunk out.

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:18.800
 The policy, I think, was to fail 50% of the first-term students, and they had an absolute way to grade spelling and commas, semicolons, and so on.

00:32:18.800 --> 00:32:39.800
 And my first few weeks, my students were doing the standard 50% absolute horrible grammar and punctuation, and they were writing idiotic stuff.

00:32:39.800 --> 00:33:07.800
 And after about five or six weeks, I told the classes that I just couldn't stand reading anymore of that kind of junk, and that from then on, I was going to ignore the mechanics and grade them totally on whether they said something sensible that I could stand to read.

00:33:07.800 --> 00:33:21.800
 And immediately, their language became fluid, and they all, from that point on, failed to fail.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:27.800
 Wow. It's almost like they were getting a chance to say what they really wanted to say finally.

00:33:27.800 --> 00:33:51.800
 Yeah, and that's how language works. The form follows the meaning, and if you focus on the form, you destroy the meaning, and that means that your form has nothing to hang on, so the form becomes extremely bad.

00:33:51.800 --> 00:34:00.800
 A deck of cards, so to speak, almost. It reminds me of biology.

00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:27.800
 Yeah, in 1968, when students were rebelling against university formalism and such, one of our biology professors said students have to be treated with authority and firmness.

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:51.800
 They want to learn to speak a language before they learn the alphabet or the rules, and she wanted to teach science the same way she conceives that people learn language.

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:59.800
 But in fact, you learn the language before you learn the alphabet.

00:34:59.800 --> 00:35:10.800
 Right. I remember reading one of A.S. Neill's accounts of the Summerhill about a boy who couldn't read, didn't want to read, had no interest in reading.

00:35:10.800 --> 00:35:26.800
 He was 16 years old, 17 years old, he still didn't want to read, and then he decided he wanted to pass some state exams to prove that he had done the high school equivalent or whatever.

00:35:26.800 --> 00:35:42.800
 And he studied for a couple months, basically taught himself how to read, became a carpenter, I think, as Neil said, and had three wonderful boys and made a living the rest of his life and had his own business and just did so well.

00:35:42.800 --> 00:35:47.800
 But it kind of made me think of that.

00:35:47.800 --> 00:36:00.800
 Yeah, I think that applies to everything. You learn the language before you learn the alphabet and how to punctuate.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:12.800
 Every five or six-year-old has thousands of words of vocabulary and can use them to communicate.

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:30.800
 When you begin studying physics or chemistry or biology, you should start with the language and learn the punctuation later.

00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:40.800
 It seems to me like when it becomes meaningful in some context that you need to know the punctuation or the grammar that is this, like you're saying it's something you'll learn at that point, right?

00:36:40.800 --> 00:36:56.800
 Yeah, exactly. It only has meaning in terms of meaning. You have to have the meaning there before the mechanics has any reality.

00:36:56.800 --> 00:37:06.800
 That makes sense. Ray, going back to Blake College, at some point, you know, the Blake College experience kind of ended for everyone.

00:37:06.800 --> 00:37:16.800
 Can you talk about that a little bit and why that happened and what were some kind of extreme positives even though it ended that came out of that?

00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:40.800
 Oh, several people went to good graduate school, and some became painters. One became a playwright, and they all went on doing what they wanted to do.

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:49.800
 And the reason it came to an end was the Vietnam War was going on.

00:37:49.800 --> 00:38:17.800
 At first, we had a visit from the cultural attaché that said he wanted to just learn what Americans were doing with the school in Mexico, but he asked me why I wasn't – if I was a linguist, a graduate student, why I hadn't become involved with the Summer Linguistics Institute project.

00:38:17.800 --> 00:38:32.800
 And that was a CIA front organization to train the Indians to be obedient, basically.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:42.800
 But when I told him I just wasn't interested in biblical translations, he put me down to some kind of subversive.

00:38:42.800 --> 00:39:11.800
 And then a couple of years later, a guy in an army uniform, which was illegal in Mexico at that time to wear a foreign uniform, he came way out to Valle de Bravo and introduced himself as a military attaché of the embassy and said he wanted to interview us.

00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:34.800
 And I don't know – I assume he asked each of us similar questions, but he did it in private, spent half an hour in my bedroom asking me what my view of the war was, what his purpose was.

00:39:34.800 --> 00:40:03.800
 Well, and I told him I thought its basic motivation was economic, and it was several months after that a series of events that could only have been organized by some higher powers took place.

00:40:03.800 --> 00:40:26.800
 In which they organized several levels, including newspaper reporters, and Madeleine Murray, and a guy who had identified himself as from Chicago.

00:40:26.800 --> 00:40:36.800
 He had clippings showing that he was a janitor posing as a communist for the FBI.

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:45.800
 And in Valle de Bravo, he ingratiated himself as an expatriate American.

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:53.800
 My father got acquainted with him, got him drunk several afternoons, learned his story.

00:40:53.800 --> 00:41:21.800
 He showed credentials from both FBI. Marine Corps retired and CIA, and that guy married Madeleine Murray, and she had the project of becoming president of Blake College.

00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:50.800
 And she – the outcome basically was that she fed stories to the embassy and the local police and the newspapers that the school was a front for Fidel Castro and for drug production and smuggling.

00:41:50.800 --> 00:42:02.800
 My gosh, so when Madeleine Murray got involved, I mean, you thought her motivations were pretty benign, didn't you?

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:31.800
 Yeah, at first she said she was – it started in Maryland. She was accused of beating up two policemen, causing one to have a heart attack, and was wanted for assault, among other things, and went to Hawaii.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:51.800
 And so it looked like she had been persecuted for her atheism, and she claimed to be a lawyer and sociology professor, and so she came to teach sociology.

00:42:51.800 --> 00:43:03.800
 But even before she got there, it came out that her plan was to have me removed and take over the school.

00:43:03.800 --> 00:43:05.800
 Unbelievable.

00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:13.800
 And so after she got there, she married this embassy contact, Dick O'Hair.

00:43:13.800 --> 00:43:23.800
 Okay. So this happened after her campaign against the schools in America, right, with the Pledge of Allegiance being got out of the classroom and so on and so forth?

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:26.800
 Yeah, all of that was prior.

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:38.800
 Wow. So the government just really didn't want American college-bound American students to be going to Mexico to learn how to think for themselves.

00:43:38.800 --> 00:43:55.800
 Yeah, especially during the Vietnam War in 1964 and 1965. They didn't want dissenters, also with the possibility of not being drafted so soon.

