 So, Ray, this idea that learning is important to life – I want to bring it back here.

00:58:01.800 --> 00:58:06.800
 I just think it's kind of the whole reason we're doing this, and I want to come back to it.

00:58:06.800 --> 00:58:18.800
 The idea that learning is an inherent desire, an inherent part of life, a part of evolution, a part of development, a part of – like, can you talk a little bit about that?

00:58:18.800 --> 00:58:19.800
 Like, where does that come from?

00:58:19.800 --> 00:58:20.800
 It doesn't have to be taught.

00:58:20.800 --> 00:58:22.800
 Like, you don't have to force someone to learn, right?

00:58:22.800 --> 00:58:24.800
 Where does learning come from?

00:58:24.800 --> 00:58:34.800
 Oh, it's something that starts with amoebas, maybe probably bacteria.

00:58:34.800 --> 00:58:43.800
 Everything is organized and cognitive all the way down to the molecular level.

00:58:43.800 --> 00:59:11.800
 As soon as it's definable as life, cognition is there, and looking at things under a microscope or following them sympathetically, few biologists are actually able to feel empathy towards a situation, an organism.

00:59:11.800 --> 00:59:36.800
 But those who look with empathy, with a Carl Rogers attitude towards life, listening rather than imposing belief, see that cognition and learning are the basic reflex of life,

00:59:36.800 --> 00:59:46.800
 where there's the ability to metabolize and move.

00:59:46.800 --> 00:59:51.800
 There is understanding and adaptation.

00:59:51.800 --> 01:00:00.800
 You wouldn't have life without adaptation, and there's always intelligence involved in adapting.

01:00:00.800 --> 01:00:08.800
 Every day you wake up, you're going to have to adapt to a whole new world.

01:00:08.800 --> 01:00:23.800
 Everything has changed while you're asleep, and the process of breathing, of your heart beating, it all is cognitive.

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:34.800
 And so you have to listen to yourself while listening to things you're understanding.

01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:42.800
 Otherwise, you will mistake what's happening in yourself for what exists in the world.

01:00:42.800 --> 01:01:01.800
 Schooling consists largely in training people to get a little model of the world in themselves, which they can then impose for the rest of their lives as they interact with the world.

01:01:01.800 --> 01:01:21.800
 But if you listen to the events in your own body, meaning that you're having empathy with what you're looking at, then you can see how much of it is your history.

01:01:21.800 --> 01:01:33.800
 And then you can see what is actually the history of the message or the behavior in front of you.

01:01:33.800 --> 01:01:36.800
 Wow, that's powerful, I think.

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:44.800
 So as an example of -- I think a lot of people think sometimes like rocks and pieces of plastic, for example, are inanimate.

01:01:44.800 --> 01:01:50.800
 But even rocks and plastic are sensitive and can listen and can learn, right?

01:01:50.800 --> 01:02:05.800
 Yes, that little encyclopedia I mentioned before, when I was seven or eight, I started looking at that because the school books weren't at all interesting.

01:02:05.800 --> 01:02:16.800
 I found J.C. Bose described in the encyclopedia and got interested in his experiments.

01:02:16.800 --> 01:02:42.800
 And he called one of his devices a crescometer. He could amplify the growth of seemingly inert vegetable or plant 10,000 times or so, so that you could see it projected on the screen as it grew.

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:59.800
 And then he would provide stimulus of various sorts and show that the plant was reacting with emotion in response.

01:02:59.800 --> 01:03:13.800
 And he said that everything shows emotion or reaction to stimulation, even minerals.

01:03:13.800 --> 01:03:40.800
 And at that time, the physicist Michael Polanyi, who later became a philosopher, when he was working on metal crystals and polymers, he was -- I don't think he knew he was following in Bose's footsteps.

01:03:40.800 --> 01:04:04.800
 But Polanyi was demonstrating that metal fatigue -- Bose said that all substances display the same properties that life does, just in a different form, including learning and fatigue and so on.

01:04:04.800 --> 01:04:33.800
 And Polanyi demonstrated that over and over through the 1920s, working with metal crystals and metallurgy, that the mechanistic idea of inert so-called material substance was very far off reality.

01:04:33.800 --> 01:04:52.800
 It wasn't a matter of atom-to-atom organization, but energy was spread out over a wide area, and the structure went below the surface.

01:04:52.800 --> 01:05:15.800
 And so that explains why airplanes have to be finely polished if they're going to be supersonic, because the stresses of a microscopic scratch on the surface will spread the influence over a great range.

01:05:15.800 --> 01:05:32.800
 And so Polanyi demonstrated that working the surface of a crystal changed the whole depth properties of resistance and memory of the crystal.

01:05:32.800 --> 01:05:42.800
 Oh, my gosh. Wow. So, I mean, I wonder sometimes how more people don't hear of these things or learn these things.

01:05:42.800 --> 01:05:53.800
 I mean, it seems like so many of us ravaged the earth as if we came into it instead of that we came out of it, from it.

01:05:53.800 --> 01:06:13.800
 And it's organic just like us. It literally is us in some way. It's just kind of crazy to me to think that so many people kind of blindly feel from that, which kind of gives us our life.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:38.800
 Yeah. I think of it as kind of a heresy against life that came to be known as mechanistic materialist science, the official science philosophy of the 20th century.

01:06:38.800 --> 01:06:51.800
 Well, you had a line once that I really like. You said "the attempt to steer a person can make it hard for them to move because it inactivates their own guidance system."

01:06:51.800 --> 01:07:03.800
 And I feel like the natural learning process at work and all of life, like the best thing we can do is just kind of get out of the way.

01:07:03.800 --> 01:07:05.800
 Do you agree with that?

