 Oh, it helps in the mechanistic system in which the theory of learning for a computer originally was that you punch holes in the card

01:10:30.800 --> 01:10:38.800
 and limit the possibilities by the holes you punch.

01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:59.800
 When you're very full of holes, you have defined its behavior most concretely, but the actual way an organism works is that each time it achieves a new synthesis,

01:10:59.800 --> 01:11:02.800
 it becomes a new question asker.

01:11:02.800 --> 01:11:08.800
 And so the whole situation changes every time you learn something.

01:11:08.800 --> 01:11:19.800
 And so you're a bigger and better question asker every time you assimilate the answer to a question or a problem.

01:11:19.800 --> 01:11:31.800
 Whereas the training doctrine is that you become more and more adept at following instructions.

01:11:31.800 --> 01:11:41.800
 Is opposition different than competition? That's a different thing entirely, right? Is opposition good versus competition?

01:11:41.800 --> 01:11:55.800
 It depends on what you're opposing. If you're opposing imposition, that's very constructive.

01:11:55.800 --> 01:12:02.800
 What about collaboration? Where does that work into it? I mean, it sounds like collaboration would just be a part of everything.

01:12:02.800 --> 01:12:05.800
 Everything is collaborative.

01:12:05.800 --> 01:12:15.800
 What are some examples of -- so, Ray, I'd love to just kind of go back a step in an individual's life, if you don't mind.

01:12:15.800 --> 01:12:18.800
 I think this is really -- I'm really loving this.

01:12:18.800 --> 01:12:34.800
 And if we were going to go to, like, a young person's life, say three years old to 11 years old, what does an ideal day of learning of life look like for a 3 to 11 year old in your eyes?

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:52.800
 Oh, it's necessary to have organisms around. The more organisms, the better as long as they aren't dangerous.

01:12:52.800 --> 01:13:00.800
 And that includes people. And there should be people talking.

01:13:00.800 --> 01:13:22.800
 That was one of the things that I thought was most important was, as a little kid, watching adults talk and listening to them and not having anything to say myself but just listening to what they were doing.

01:13:22.800 --> 01:13:36.800
 And meanwhile, I would be attending to whatever might be the concern a more private way.

01:13:36.800 --> 01:14:02.800
 For example, watching how the hairs on my arm made rainbows as light as they turned in the light, and starting to wonder how light works, what light is in them, how the eye perceives it.

01:14:02.800 --> 01:14:22.800
 And the total openness, hearing what's going on in the world, not either approving it or disapproving it, especially just knowing that it's happening.

01:14:22.800 --> 01:14:34.800
 But then having the undefined world all around you, watching how flies wash their face, for example.

01:14:34.800 --> 01:14:43.800
 That's really cool. So this is like science beginning to begin its life in you, right?

01:14:43.800 --> 01:15:00.800
 Yeah. My first little experiment, I think I was about a year old or so, watching when I cried, how the water in my eyes affected the image.

01:15:00.800 --> 01:15:03.800
 It affected the what?

01:15:03.800 --> 01:15:13.800
 It affected the image, refracting the light, changing the color, and distorting the image.

01:15:13.800 --> 01:15:17.800
 Wow. So Ray, what is science?

01:15:17.800 --> 01:15:27.800
 And at a fundamental level, away from the business of science, in a simple way, can you sum up, what is science?

01:15:27.800 --> 01:15:40.800
 It's open learning, the idea that learning isn't finished.

01:15:40.800 --> 01:15:55.800
 You're always wanting to check it against reality, and reality is always changing, and so it's always giving you opportunities for changing your mind.

01:15:55.800 --> 01:15:58.800
 So truly, a never-ending process.

01:15:58.800 --> 01:16:06.800
 Yeah, that's where science and education are the same thing, really.

01:16:06.800 --> 01:16:07.800
 Wow, that's really cool.

01:16:07.800 --> 01:16:15.800
 So I love how you talked about a community of organisms, and not necessarily people, right, but just all of life.

01:16:15.800 --> 01:16:27.800
 It's really important, and it reminds me of the expression, "It takes a village." You're taking that expression into a very practically speaking that it does take a village, right?

01:16:27.800 --> 01:16:37.800
 Oh, yeah. Flies and snails, and plants, and everything included.

01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:39.800
 That's really cool.

01:16:39.800 --> 01:16:54.800
 Aside from that, that village of organisms, if you were going to make available a library or an atelier, a kind of workshop or learning space for a young learner, would you have anything in there?

01:16:54.800 --> 01:16:59.800
 Could you talk about what you might have in that workshop, or what kind of books you would put in there?

